{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \DK. Top of your strong diamond honors is a safe, aggressive start, and it lets you see dummy before deciding where to go next.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\S and need ten tricks. Between your hand and dummy you have plenty of spade tricks plus the \HA, but you are missing the \HK, so one extra trick must come from the heart suit where you hold A\HQ opposite small cards. The plan is to lead a low heart from your hand toward dummy's holding and finesse the queen for that tenth trick. The king is missing and could sit on either side, so the finesse is about even money, your best practical chance.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \DK, which looks like top of a strong diamond holding; you have no diamonds in hand and a singleton coming, so plan to ruff diamonds rather than waste trumps on them. Draw trumps, keeping a low heart in hand, then lead that small heart toward dummy and play the queen if second hand follows low; with the king missing on an unknown side, this is roughly a fifty-fifty shot. If the finesse loses, you still have your spade winners, the heart ace, and club ruffs in the short trump hand to fall back on. Counting these, your trumps plus the side tricks bring you to the ten you need when the finesse comes home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
By counting your sure tricks first you knew exactly that the heart suit was the one trick you had to find, and timing the finesse after drawing trumps protected it. Nicely judged - you gave yourself the best honest chance and brought home a tight game.}
