{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H5. With no clear sequence or singleton, leading from your longest non-trump suit is a reasonable, safe choice against four spades.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\S and need ten tricks. You have strong spade trumps, the top diamonds, and the \HA, but you are missing the \HK, so your tenth trick must come from the A\HQ in your hand opposite dummy's small hearts. The plan is to draw trumps and lead a low heart toward your A\HQ, finessing the queen. NS hold 24 of the 40, leaving the defense 16, and the missing king could be on either side - the finesse is about even money and is the decisive trick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H5, which looks like a small card from length rather than an honor lead; you can win the \HA or, better, use the chance to set up the finesse position. Draw trumps watching for the outstanding trump honor, cash your diamonds, then lead a low heart toward your A\HQ and play the queen if the next hand follows low - with the king unseen on either side, this is roughly fifty-fifty. If the finesse loses you fall a trick short, so this is the make-or-break play. When the queen holds, your trumps, the top diamonds, and the heart ace combine to give you exactly ten.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
By counting first you knew the heart finesse was the trick you had to find, so you drew trumps and kept your entries to take it cleanly. Nicely judged - that disciplined order of play is exactly what brings home a close game.}
