{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \D8. Against notrump, the eight is the right card from your long, strong diamonds, leading your best suit to set up tricks while you still have entries.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3\N and need nine tricks. Your hearts give four top tricks and can be developed for a fifth, and the clubs in \CAQJT opposite \C965 are your richest source of new tricks, so develop clubs for the bulk of your winners. Spades supply the swing: you hold \SAQ4 opposite \S9762, with the ace but not the king, so a finesse leading low toward the \SAQ can bring up the ninth trick. Plan to combine the club development with the spade finesse.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \D8, which against notrump looks like a long-suit lead. By the rule of eleven, eleven minus eight leaves three cards higher than the eight outside West's hand, and all three sit in your hand and dummy, so his partner has none higher than the eight, telling you West holds the diamond strength. Hold up or win as the suit dictates, then drive out the club honours to set up your club tricks. For the ninth trick, lead low toward your \SAQ and finesse the queen if the next hand follows low: the king is missing and could be on either side, so this is about even money, your best route to nine. If it loses, the diamonds may have been knocked out, so cash your established winners promptly.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The rule of eleven told you the diamond strength was on your left, counting first pointed you to clubs as the trick source, and the spade finesse was the well-timed ninth trick. Bringing those three pieces together is first-rate notrump play. Excellent work.}
