{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \CT. From this club holding the ten is the standard top-of-an-interior-sequence lead, a safe start that may set up a trick without conceding one.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\H and need ten tricks. Your trumps are strong, the \CA gives a sure trick, and the diamonds can be developed and ruffed for more, so your floor sits around seven or eight. The extra spade trick is available: you hold \SAQ9 opposite \ST432, with the ace but not the king, so plan to lead low toward the \SAQ and finesse the queen. With trumps this good the game is safe regardless, so the spade finesse is for an overtrick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \CT, which looks like top of an interior sequence rather than a singleton. Win the \CA, draw trumps, and set up your diamonds with ruffs as needed. For the spade play, lead a low spade from dummy toward your \SAQ and finesse the queen if the next hand follows low. The king is missing and could be with either defender, so it is about even money: if it wins you score an overtrick, and if it loses your trumps, the \CA, and the diamond tricks still bring in all ten. Nothing about the contract turns on the guess.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Because you counted first, you knew the strong trumps and side tricks already made the game, so the spade finesse was pure upside. Keeping clear which tricks are guaranteed lets you take the even-money chance with ease. Lovely play.}
