{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \S6. Against notrump, a fourth-best spade from your longest suit is the standard choice, working to set up your length while you hold entries.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 2\N and need eight tricks. Your hearts in \HAKT97 opposite \HJ43 are your richest source, worth two top tricks now and four once developed, so hearts are the suit to build. Add the \DA and the \CAK and your winners come together nicely. Spades supply the swing trick: you hold \SAQ5 opposite \ST972, with the ace but not the king, so a finesse leading low toward the \SAQ can produce the eighth trick. The contract is low and safe, so combine the heart development with the spade finesse.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \S6, which against notrump looks like a fourth-best. By the rule of eleven, eleven minus six leaves five cards higher than the six outside West's hand, and all five sit in your hand and dummy, so his partner holds none higher than the six. Win the trick in the right hand and develop your hearts, which give you the bulk of your tricks. For the spade trick, lead low toward your \SAQ and finesse the queen if the next hand follows low: the king is missing and could be on either side, so it is about even money, your best chance for the eighth trick. If it loses, your hearts, the \DA, and the top clubs still bring the eight home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The rule of eleven confirmed the spade picture, counting first pointed you to hearts as the engine, and the spade finesse was the well-placed swing trick. Putting those reads together is exactly how to handle a notrump partscore. Excellent work.}
