{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \SJ. From a strong spade sequence the jack is the standard top-of-sequence lead, a safe and constructive start that builds tricks in your long suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 4\H and need ten tricks. Your trumps in \HKQJ932 opposite \HAT876 are outstanding, worth six tricks, and with the \DA, \DK plus the \DT your sure tricks already sit around nine. The extra trick comes from spades, where you hold \SAQ opposite \S432: you have the ace but not the king, so plan to lead low toward the \SAQ and finesse the queen. With trumps this strong the game is safe regardless, so the spade finesse is for an overtrick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \SJ, which looks like top of a sequence, leading toward your \SAQ. This is convenient: you can play low from dummy and let the lead run to your queen, or win the ace and later lead toward the queen. Either way the king is missing and could be with either defender, so it is roughly even money: if the queen scores you gain an overtrick, and if the king is wrong your six trumps and the strong diamonds still bring in all ten tricks. The contract is not at risk on the guess.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
You counted your trumps and diamonds first, saw the game was locked up, and used the helpful spade lead to take the finesse for an overtrick. Recognizing a friendly lead while keeping your sure tricks in mind is just the right approach. Beautifully done.}
